english:
  title: On the Cold Jade Tower of Changwon
  author: Lee Seok-hyeong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A lifetime I've spurned the sour pedantry of scholars,
    Yet every time I climb the high tower, I lean upon the railing.
    Mountains wear their misty robes and drift through open windows,
    Streams hold the bamboo's shadow, chilling all who pass.
    I almost believe the crane's back touches heaven's three layers,
    And see the tortoise's head commanding all four seas.
    I laugh—in age my madness only deepens,
    When will this poetic passion finally subside?

    Towering peaks press down upon the distant sea,
    And the sublime vistas open wide before my eyes.
    Clouds have drifted for ten thousand ages—how much remains?
    The cranes departed ages past and never shall return.
    On the broken cliff, the platform mirrors only the pale moon,
    The weathered stone bears no inscription, only moss of jade.
    Of all those distant years, who remains to ask?
    I pour a cup in honor of this timeless wind.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'three heavens' and 'four seas' are classical references to the highest reaches and widest expanses of the world, emphasizing the tower's commanding perspective.
  - key: ''
    value: The crane and tortoise are symbols of longevity and spiritual transcendence in East Asian poetry, suggesting the speaker's aspiration to transcend mortal concerns.
  - key: ''
    value: The tower's naming—'Cold Jade'—suggests both the austere beauty of the natural landscape and the speaker's refined, solitary temperament.
